2019 LF Company Business Travel Data Analysis

by Thomas Ying

L&F Company (L&F) is a multinational corporation which span the entire global supply chain for consumer goods including trading, logistics, distribution and retail. Because of the business nature, staffs of L&F from different departments travel frequently throughout the year. The company spends quite an amount of cost in this area.

To manage cooperate travel in a systematic way such as giving regulation in buying flight ticket and litmiting travel expenses, L&F appointed different travel agencies in its operating regions to manage cooperate travel matters of the company. These travel agencies expert in Corporate travel management (CTM), which is the function of managing a companys strategic approach to travel, day-to-day operation of the corporate travel program, traveler safety and security, and travel and expenses data management. In other words, CTM helps L&F to decide on the class of service which employees are allowed to fly, negotiates corporate fares/rates with airlines and hotels and determines how the travel budget to be used.

This dataset is prepared by L&F, which contained approximately 31,000 travel application record of L&F in 2019.

Variable descriptions

Here is a brief introduction for each variables in the dataset:

Name Description
Ref_No travel application no. by person
Operating_Group the main department
Stream stream under department
Product_Group product group under stream
Division division under product group
Passenger_Name changed to code because of privacy
Invoice_No invoice no. of the trip
Invoice_Date invoice issuing date
Departure_Date date of departure
PNR_Creation_Date passenger name record creation date
Routing in IATA 3 digit code
SL_Haul short or long haul or connection flight
Reason_Code 2 digit code to describe why fare is allowed
Travel_Agent travel agency name
Country_Region the country/region travel agency located
Trip_Purpose purpose of business travel
Class_Code 1 digit class code of the flight
Airline_Code IATA 2 digit code of the airline
Original_Fare basic fare of the flight ticket
Tax tax amount have to pay
Discount amount deducted from original fare
Net_Fare original fare + tax - discount
Transaction_Fee service fee to travel agency
Lower_Logical_Fare the lowest ticket fare the travler should take logically
Premium net fare - lower logical fare

What is the structure of your dataset?

After wrangling, there are 28777 records of business trip from L&F in 2019. The dataset can be divided into 3 parts by the function of columns. From the first column to the fifth column(Division) are the info of the travelers; the sixth column(Invoice_No) to the seventeenth column(Airline_Code) are the info of the travel product; the eighteenth column(Original_Fare) to the last column are the info about price of the product. The fisrt two part of the dataset are all string and datetime, then all price variables are continuous numerical data.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

I'm interested in two aspects. The first is to figure out the travel pattern of L&F in 2019 by 4W1H - What(trip purpose), Who(operating group), When(departure date), Where(destination), How(airline). The second is to focus on flight expenses such as the top spending operating groups and how much did they spend on business trip yearly, and even deeply in which period the operating groups spend the most and the expenses they spend on traveling to some popular destination.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

The investigation will centre around Operating Group and three main numeric variables - Net Fare, Discount and Premium. All visualization are intened to show relationships between these four variables and other attributes.

Univariate Exploration

In this section, I will investigate distributions of individual variables. Mainly the count number of the categorical variables and distribution of the main numeric variable of interest - Net Fare, Discount and Premium.

For Operating Group, SCS2 is the group which recorded the most travel record in 2019 with over 4000 times, following by LF Asia Direct which traveled around 4000 times. Staffs from SCS3 and LF Logistics both traveled over 3000 times in 2019. SCS4, LF Products, SCS1, LF Europe and Cobalt Fashion all recorded over 1000 times of business trips. All the operating groups mentioned above compose the main influence of travel in L&F. Of course these are only count numbers and cost of travel can be vary, we will see the expenses they spend in the next part. For Country/Region, L&F as a Hong Kong based cooperation, it is no wonder that most of the travlers are from Hong Kong. The following region, Shanghai, Shenzhen in China, and India, are well known of manufacturing so it is not surprised that they have far more travelers than other regions. For Trip Purpose, L&F as a trading and supply chain company, customer visit, quality control and supplier visit are naturally the main purpose of business travel. These three purposes recorded over or neraly 5000 counts.

I also want to know the frequency of destintion, airline and long/short haul flight. Since Routing and Airline code are shown as XXX/XXX or XX/XX, I need to separate them before counting.

In [26]:
# split the string by / then stack the results into plural rows
def sep_table(column, rename):
    table = df.drop(column, axis=1).join(df[column].str.split('/', expand=True).stack().reset_index(drop=True, level=1).rename(rename))
    table = table.replace('', np.nan).dropna(subset=[rename])
    return table

""" In the previous section I separated Routing and Airline Code into Destination and Airline for easier counting,
but the problem is that sum of Net Fare would be multipled when grouping by Destination or Airline because some rows 
are separted into N rows now. Therefore, for those rows which are '1 to N', their Net Fare, Discount and Premium
need to be divided by N."""

def number_div_count(df_name):
    define_col = ['Ref_No', 'Passenger_Name','Invoice_No','Net_Fare']
    
    # create a column to show how many rows do the original row separated into
    n_count = df_name.groupby(define_col)['Net_Fare'].count().rename_axis(define_col).reset_index(name='counts')
    table = df_name.set_index(define_col)
    n_count = n_count.set_index(define_col)
    table_count = table.join(n_count, on=define_col).reset_index()
    
    # three numeric variables are divided by the count number
    table_count['Net_Fare'] = table_count['Net_Fare']/table_count['counts']
    table_count['Discount'] = table_count['Discount']/table_count['counts']
    table_count['Premium '] = table_count['Premium']/table_count['counts']
    
    return table_count

# use to function to the dataframes I created for Destination and Airline before
Destination = number_div_count(Destination)
Airline = number_div_count(Airline)

# create function for getting top n results only
def top_table(df, column, agg_column, head_num):
    result = df.groupby(column)[agg_column].sum().sort_values(ascending=False).head(head_num)
    return result
